prompt:
The image tool I maintain tracks which 4 KiB blocks of a fixed-extent volume image are in use, and the ad-hoc byte-per-block array we use today wastes memory and is slow to scan. I want a proper bitmap library: bitvec.h and bitvec.c, C17, stdint.h/stddef.h only, no allocation anywhere -- the caller owns the word storage, the library only ever touches those words.

Exact surface (the tool and its fsck both build against this):

    #define BV_WORDS(nbits) (((nbits) + 63u) / 64u)

    typedef struct {
        uint64_t *words;   /* caller storage, BV_WORDS(nbits) elements */
        size_t    nbits;
    } bitvec;

    int    bv_init(bitvec *bv, uint64_t *words, size_t nbits);
    int    bv_set(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_clear(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_flip(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_test(const bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_set_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
    int    bv_clear_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
    size_t bv_count(const bitvec *bv);
    long   bv_count_range(const bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
    long   bv_next_set(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);
    long   bv_next_clear(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);

Rules, learned the hard way from the fsck:

- bv_init: -1 when bv or words is NULL or nbits is 0; otherwise zero all BV_WORDS(nbits) words (the caller's array is usually stack garbage) and return 0.
- Single-bit ops take a block index. Out of range (i >= nbits) returns -1 and must not touch anything. bv_test returns 0 or 1 (or -1 out of range); set/clear/flip return 0 on success. Bit 0 is the least significant bit of words[0], bit 64 the LSB of words[1], and so on.
- Ranges are half-open [lo, hi). STRICT bounds: lo <= hi <= nbits or the call returns -1 having changed nothing -- never silently clamp; the fsck feeds untrusted extents and needs the error. lo == hi is a valid no-op returning 0. Ranges must handle any alignment: inside one word, exactly on word seams, straddling several words.
- bv_count is a popcount of the map. bv_count_range counts inside [lo, hi) with the same strict bounds, -1 on a bad range.
- bv_next_set / bv_next_clear return the smallest index >= from whose bit is set / clear, or -1 when there is none (from >= nbits is also -1). This is the hot path when the allocator looks for a free block, so skipping whole zero (or full) words rather than testing bit by bit is the point of the exercise -- but only the results are graded.
- Bits at positions >= nbits in the last word must NEVER be set, no matter what combination of range ops runs; bv_count and the scanners must stay exact for maps whose size is not a multiple of 64.
- No globals, no statics, no I/O.

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_bitvec.c are fixed.
